  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\eta:S\\circ F\\Rightarrow F\\circ S.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Symplectic Preservation Law.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\eta_X^{*}\\omega_{F\\circ S(X)}\n=\n\\omega_{S\\circ F(X)}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $S$ be a scaling functor and $F$ a structure functor.  \nThere are two routes:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nS\\circ F,\n\\qquad\nF\\circ S.\n\\end{equation}\n\nA natural transformation compares these routes:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\eta:S\\circ F\\Rightarrow F\\circ S.\n\\end{equation}\n\nTo preserve dynamics, the bridge must preserve the symplectic form:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\eta_X^{*}\\omega_{F\\circ S(X)}\n=\n\\omega_{S\\circ F(X)}.\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nScaling and structural translation are compatible only when the categorical bridge preserves phase-space geometry.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
